******
[1] Denmark
Date: Tue 12 Aug 2014
Source: BBC News [edited]
http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28761463


Danish officials say they suspect that sausage contaminated with _Listeria [monocytogenes]_ bacteria has killed at least 12 people.

The infection is thought to have come from pork sausages called rullepoelse [rolled sausage], made by a firm in Hedehusene, near the capital Copenhagen. The product has now been withdrawn from sale.

So far 8 other people have tested positive for _Listeria_. Deaths occur mostly among people who are already in a weak condition. The outbreak began last September [2013]. Denmark's state health agency SSI says the outbreak is believed to be under control.

Health officials are trying to determine if any of the contaminated meat was sent to schools or restaurants, or was exported.

Listeriosis symptoms often include fever, headache, diarrhoea, and vomiting. The incubation period can last 2 months, making it often difficult to trace the source of contamination.

_Listeria_ can spread from delicatessen food even when kept cool in a refrigerator.

